result.execSummary:
Kendall Bernard Russell was extradited to another county, state or jurisdiction. Extradition means Kendall Bernard Russell was accused or convicted of an offense in another county, state or jurisdiction and was taken there to face their charge(s) or conviction.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.
result.caption: State of Wisconsin vs. Kendall Bernard Russell

records.descr: Records of prosec. are converted data. See file.

records.addlTxt: Fugitive Complaint, Warrant and Waiver of Extradition forwarded to Governor of Wisconsin.

Defendant Kendall Bernard Russell in court, in custody.  Jon D. Seifert appeared for the State of Wisconsin.    Defendant confirms he received a copy of Fugitive Complaint.  Court advises defendant he's being held on a warrant out of State of Minnesota Case No. 62-CR-14-6561 simple robbery, failed to complete Teen Challenge Program and absconded probation.  Court explains Extradition process and advises defendant of rights.  Defendant waives extradition.  Waiver of Extradition filed with Court.  Court finds defendant waives his rights to extradition and remands him to Pepin County Sheriff's Department to forthwith be turned over to Ramsey County, Minnesota.
Defendant Kendall Bernard Russell in court, in custody.  Jon D. Seifert appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
